Welcome to notebook seven — information theory. The entropy of a discrete random variable x with p m f p is — h of x equals the negative sum, over x, of p of x, times log p of x. Equivalently, the expectation of negative log p of capital x.

For continuous x, the differential entropy uses an integral instead of a sum. Some properties differ, but the machine learning applications focus on the discrete case for classification.

The base of the logarithm chooses the units. Log base two gives bits. Natural log gives nats — used in machine learning almost universally. Log base ten gives dits, or hartleys — rare. We will use natural log throughout, matching most m l code.

Three ways to read entropy. First, as surprise. Negative log p of x is the surprise of seeing outcome x. Rare events with small p have high surprise. Certain events with p equal to one carry zero surprise. Entropy is the expected surprise.

Second, as uncertainty. Entropy is maximum when all outcomes are equally likely — the uniform distribution. And zero when one outcome is certain. High entropy means high uncertainty. Low entropy means predictable.

Third, as a compression bound. Shannon's coding theorem says — the optimal lossless code for outcomes from distribution p uses on average h of x bits per symbol. You cannot compress below entropy. You should aim to get close to it.

A few examples. A fair coin has entropy equal to negative one half log one half, minus one half log one half. Equal to log two, which is one bit. Maximum uncertainty for a binary variable. A biased coin with p equal to zero point nine has entropy about zero point four seven bits. Much less uncertainty. We mostly expect heads. A deterministic distribution has entropy zero. No uncertainty.

A few properties. Entropy is non negative. Entropy is at most log k for k outcomes. Equality if and only if uniform. Uniform distributions are maximum entropy. And joint entropy h of x and y is at most h of x plus h of y, with equality if and only if x and y are independent. This is called subadditivity.

Now cross entropy. Suppose data comes from p, but you describe it — compress it, predict it — with a different distribution q. The cross entropy is the expected surprise of q evaluated on p's samples. H of p and q equals the negative sum, over x, of p of x, times log q of x. Equivalently, the expectation, under x drawn from p, of negative log q of capital x.

When q equals p, cross entropy equals entropy. H of p and p equals h of p. Otherwise, h of p and q is strictly greater than h of p. Using the wrong distribution to describe data costs extra surprise.

The classification connection. In supervised learning, p is the empirical distribution of labels — often a one hot vector for a single example, putting all probability on the true class y. And q is the model's prediction p hat. The cross entropy loss for one example is — negative sum, over k, of y sub k, times log p hat sub k.

For a one hot target with y at the true class equal to one, this collapses to negative log p hat at the true class. The single number — negative log of the predicted probability of the correct class. This is the loss every classification network minimizes.

It is also exactly the negative log likelihood under a categorical model. Cross entropy and n l l are the same thing. Different names, same object.

The binary case. For bernoulli with predicted probability p hat and label y, the binary cross entropy is — negative y, times log p hat, minus one minus y, times log of one minus p hat. This is what n n dot b c e loss computes.

Now k l divergence — the "distance" from q to p. The most used quantity in probabilistic m l. Defined as — d k l of p, given q, equals the sum, over x, of p of x, times log of p of x divided by q of x. Equivalently, the expectation, under x drawn from p, of log p of x divided by q of x.

The equivalent rewrite to memorize — d k l of p given q equals h of p and q, the cross entropy, minus h of p, the entropy.

K l divergence is the extra surprise from using q instead of p. Cross entropy minus entropy. Always non negative. Zero if and only if p equals q.

A few important properties — and one famous non property. D k l of p given q is greater than or equal to zero. This is called gibbs inequality. Proved using jensen's inequality on the concave log function. D k l equals zero if and only if p equals q almost everywhere.

Not symmetric. D k l of p given q is generally not equal to d k l of q given p. This is why k l is called a divergence, not a distance. It does not satisfy the distance axioms. The asymmetry matters. D k l of p given q penalizes q for having low mass where p has high mass — called mode covering. D k l of q given p does the opposite — called mode seeking.

K l does not satisfy the triangle inequality.

The classification loss connection. For one hot labels, where h of p equals zero, the cross entropy equals d k l of p given q, plus h of p — which is just d k l. So minimizing cross entropy equals minimizing k l equals pulling the predicted distribution toward the true distribution. Three different framings of the same objective.

The variational connection. Variational inference, variational auto encoders, k l regularized reinforcement learning, r l h f, distillation — all use k l as the unit of distance between probability distributions.

A subtle point. D k l of p given q is undefined, or infinite, wherever q of x is zero but p of x is positive. This is why classification losses often clamp predicted probabilities to a small range above zero and below one — to avoid negative log of zero, which is infinity.

Now mutual information. How much does knowing y tell you about x? The answer is the mutual information. I of x and y equals d k l of the joint p of x and y, given the product of marginals p of x, times p of y.

It is the k l divergence between the joint and the product of marginals. If x and y are independent, the joint equals the product of marginals, and the mutual information is zero. Otherwise it is positive — measuring how far from independent the two variables are.

Equivalent expressions worth memorizing. I of x and y equals h of x, minus the conditional entropy h of x given y. Equivalently, h of y, minus h of y given x. Equivalently, h of x plus h of y, minus h of x and y.

Reading them — mutual information is the reduction in uncertainty about x once you observe y, or vice versa. It is also symmetric. I of x and y equals i of y and x, unlike k l.

Bounds. I of x and y is between zero and the minimum of h of x and h of y. I of x and y equals zero if and only if x and y are independent. I of x and x equals h of x — knowing x perfectly tells you all of h of x.

A machine learning angle. Mutual information shows up in feature selection. Pick features with high mutual information with y. They are informative about the label.

Information bottleneck. Trade off i of z and y, which should be high — predictive — against i of z and x, which should be low — compressed. A theoretical lens on representation learning.

Info n c e and contrastive learning. Sim c l r, mo co, clip — all train representations to maximize a lower bound on mutual information between augmentations or between modalities.

Variational auto encoders. Beta v a e's add a penalty proportional to i of z and x to learn disentangled representations.

Self supervised pre training. Predict masked or future content. High mutual information between visible and hidden parts is what makes the task informative.

Now jensen's inequality — the workhorse. A convex function f lies below every chord. Equivalently, for a random variable x — f of the expectation of x is less than or equal to the expectation of f of x.

For concave f, the inequality flips. F of the expectation of x is greater than or equal to the expectation of f of x.

This is jensen's inequality, and it is the source of probably half the proofs in probability and information theory.

Why does it matter here? First, k l divergence is non negative. Apply jensen to the concave function negative log. Negative d k l of p given q equals the expectation, under p, of log of q of x divided by p of x. By jensen, less than or equal to log of the expectation of q of x divided by p of x. Which equals log of one. Which is zero. So k l is greater than or equal to zero. Three lines, profound consequences.

Second, the evidence lower bound, e l b o. Variational inference uses jensen to bound log p of x from below by a tractable expression, then maximizes that bound. The entire v a e training objective is a jensen derived inequality.

Third, concavity of entropy. H of p is a concave function of p. Hence bayesian model averaging — a mixture — has entropy higher than the mixture weighted average of the components entropies.

Fourth, convexity of negative log likelihood for exponential family. Makes m l e for exponential family distributions a convex optimization problem. Solved efficiently. No bad local minima.

Jensen is one of those identities you will apply over and over without explicitly invoking it. Once you spot the move — concave function, expectation moves in — the proofs that seemed magical become natural.

Now the information theory bridge to machine learning losses. Bring it all together. The information theoretic interpretation of the standard losses.

Cross entropy classification loss. Minimizing the cross entropy of empirical p and model q over theta is equivalent to minimizing the k l divergence — since the entropy of the empirical distribution is constant. You are pulling the model's predicted distribution as close as possible to the empirical one.

K l regularized reinforcement learning — t r p o, p p o. Add beta times the k l divergence of the new policy from the old policy, to the policy gradient objective, so updates cannot move the policy too far per step. K l acts as a trust region constraint.

R l h f. Reward equals the reward model score, minus beta times the k l divergence of the policy from the supervised fine tuned reference. The k l penalty keeps the r l h f tuned model from drifting too far from the s f t baseline.

Distillation. Train student q to match teacher p by minimizing the k l divergence of teacher from student. The teacher's soft probabilities carry more information than hard labels — sometimes called dark knowledge.

Variational inference, e l b o, v a e's. Maximize the expectation under q of log p of x given z, minus the k l divergence of q of z given x, from the prior p of z. The first term is reconstruction. The second term is a k l regularizer that keeps the posterior close to the prior.

Info n c e for contrastive learning. A lower bound on the mutual information between paired positives. Maximizing it pushes positives together and negatives apart in representation space.

Information bottleneck. Train representations to maximize i of z and y, while minimizing i of z and x. Extract only the information relevant to predicting y. A theoretical lens, sometimes operationalized in practice.

These all share the same vocabulary. Entropies, cross entropies, k l divergences. Once you see them, you can read modern machine learning papers fluently.

Let us close with where information theory appears in machine learning. It is the second most used branch of math in modern m l, after linear algebra. Every probabilistic objective lives here.

Cross entropy classification. Standard loss for every classification model. Multi class softmax plus cross entropy is the negative log likelihood, equal to the k l divergence between empirical and model distributions.

Binary cross entropy, log loss. Same story, two class version. Used in logistic regression, generative adversarial networks for the discriminator, and binary classification.

Label smoothing. Replace one hot — zero zero one zero — with a slightly softened version. Adds entropy to the target. Softens the cross entropy gradient. Less overconfidence. Pure information theory move.

V a e training. Maximize the e l b o. Reconstruction — cross entropy or gaussian n l l — minus the k l divergence of the encoder posterior from the prior.

Diffusion model training. Each denoising step has an e l b o like k l objective. Closed form for gaussian conditionals.

P p o and t r p o. K l divergence trust regions on policy updates.

R l h f. K l penalty against the s f t reference model.

Distillation. Student matches teacher's softmax distribution via k l, sometimes with temperature scaling.

Contrastive learning. Sim c l r, mo co, clip. Maximize info n c e — a mutual information lower bound between views or modalities.

Information bottleneck networks. Explicitly regularize i of z and x to learn minimal sufficient representations.

Mutual information for feature selection. Pick features x sub i with highest mutual information with the label y.

Information gain in decision trees. Splits chosen to maximize the entropy of y, minus the conditional entropy of y given the split. Exactly mutual information at the split.

Maximum entropy modeling. Choose p to maximize entropy subject to moment constraints. Equivalent to fitting an exponential family distribution.

Bits per character or bits per token in language models. A direct reading of cross entropy in compression units. State of the art reporting in language modeling uses bits per character.

Calibration. Compare predicted distribution to empirical via reliability diagrams and expected calibration error. Entropy aware variants include the brier score decomposition.

The next notebook covers sampling, the central limit theorem, and hypothesis testing. The law of large numbers, the c l t, monte carlo, and a b testing. Closing the probability repo and bridging to applied statistics.
